snippet.textDisplay: It'd be nice if this mRNA vaccine worked, but don't pin your hopes on it.  There's basically no real research showing this kind of vaccine working.  It is entirely possible that it simply won't do anything at all.  It's just a protein and it's unclear why or whether the immune system would respond to it at all, much less with the right kinds of cells to build recognition.  Also, could all the people online who are freaking out about govt officials who knew about the virus in February just stop?  The This Week In Virology podcast did their first episode mentioning SARS-CoV-2 on January 12.  Anyone who was following virology or interested in public health knew about this back then.  It was not secret.  China was lying their ass off, of course, but the administration and general public just didn't give a shit.  As it is, it seems like a lot of the public is just angry because there are some people who actually keep up with this stuff.  The New York Times published their first story about this virus on January 6th.  Discussions were being had on ProMedMail on January 8th.  This thing did not just pop out of nowhere in mid-March.  The people for who it seemed this way are just victims of their own ignorance.  If you fill your life with celebrity gossip and fashion and stuff, you're not going to know about virology.  Don't slam the people who do follow virology for knowing things.  Everyone has different interests, you can't know everything.  And if they HAD screamed and yelled that this was going to be a huge pandemic, not only would they not have had the evidence to convince anyone (because China was lying), but those who didn't give a shit about virology would aggressively downplay it until the virus was on their doorstep anyway.  Don't pretend otherwise.

snippet.textDisplay:
I have thought about the situation we are facing as a civilization for a while, and I have realised that the world is faced with a complex paradox, I call it the Pandemic Paradox.
The danger with very infectious diseases like COVID-19 isn't its deadliness in the end. People will survive, but while they are in their beds for weeks on end, that means that they are not an active member of society. This mixed with the fact that this virus has an symptomless incubation period of up to 2 weeks, means that thousands and thousand could be active infectors. This could mean that millions of people would get sick, and that millions would stay home. This could lead to whole economies collapsing. But, when governments try to curb this pandemic, they ALSO force millions to stay at home in quarantine, which in turn means that nobody will work or buy stuff, creating an economic collapse.
I honestly don't know the answer to this question.

Stay healthy out there folks. Tip your delivery drivers whether you’re ordering groceries, postmartes, doordash, or domino’s - we don’t get the luxury of working from home and are quite literally on the front lines of this covid-19 virus. I made 24$ last night from 5pm-1:30am
This is unacceptable 🤷‍♂️- that doesn’t even cover the gas I used. This isn’t the time to be stingy - especially when we’re out here battling the effects of social distancing but without actually having that luxury. If one of us gets sick, 9/10 we downplay symptoms in order to continue to work because we simply can’t afford it. I was stiffed on half of all of my runs, and only had two tip over 5$. We have to do better about looking out for one another. The delivery charge does NOT go to us- it goes to the store. I’d say being able to order literally anything at your fingertips warrants at least 3-5$, I don’t think that’s asking for too much 🤷‍♂️. Stay safe, stay healthy, but most importantly #tipyourdrivers
